\section*{Characterizing Trees}

We are interested in characterizing trees, which, by definition, are connected graphs with no cycles. A key result states that a graph with $n$ vertices is a tree if and only if it is connected and has $n-1$ edges. This equivalence provides multiple ways to verify whether a graph is a tree.

\begin{theorem}
Let $G$ be a graph with $n$ vertices and $m$ edges. The following are equivalent:
(1) $G$ is connected and acyclic.
(2) $G$ is a tree, so $m=n-1$.
(3) $G$ is connected and $m=n-1$.
\end{theorem}

The proof of this equivalence involves demonstrating that (1) implies (2), (2) implies (3), and (3) implies (1). We will first focus on proving the implication from connectedness and acyclicity to having $m = n-1$ edges. This can be accomplished by induction, leveraging the properties of leaves in a connected graph. Specifically, we can remove a leaf and apply induction to show that the resulting graph has exactly $n-1$ edges.

\section*{Proof Strategy}

To prove (1) $\Rightarrow$ (2), we assume that $G$ is connected and acyclic. We then employ the "longest path trick" – a technique for analyzing graphs – which guarantees the existence of at least one leaf in $G$. By removing this leaf and applying induction, we can establish that $G$ has exactly $n-1$ edges.

\textbf{★} \textit{Exam Note: Be prepared to state the theorem and outline the strategy for proving its equivalence.}

Next, we consider the implication (2) $\Rightarrow$ (3). This direction involves assuming that $G$ is connected and has $m = n-1$ edges. The goal here is to demonstrate that $G$ must be acyclic. To do this, we proceed by contradiction: we assume that $G$ contains a cycle and then derive a contradiction based on the assumption that $m=n-1$.

If we assume $G$ has a cycle, we can remove an edge from that cycle to obtain a smaller connected graph. This process can be repeated until no cycles remain.

