\section*{Equivalence of Tree Properties}

A fundamental characterization of trees revolves around their connectivity and acyclicity. A graph $G$ with $n$ vertices and $m$ edges is a tree if and only if it is connected and acyclic. This equivalence implies several other relationships: every two vertices in $G$ have a path between them, and the number of edges is exactly one less than the number of vertices ($m = n-1$).

\begin{theorem}
Let $G$ be a finite graph with $n$ vertices and $m$ edges. The following are equivalent:
    (1) $G$ is connected and acyclic.
    (2) Every two vertices in $G$ have a path between them.
    (3) $G$ has exactly $m=n-1$ edges.
\end{theorem}

The proof of this equivalence often proceeds by contradiction, which can be particularly illuminating for students. While direct or contrapositive proofs are also valid approaches, the contradictory argument highlights the interconnectedness of these properties.

\section*{Cycle Breaking and Forest Structure}

A key technique in understanding trees is the concept of cycle breaking. By repeatedly removing edges from a graph until it becomes acyclic, we can systematically transform it into a tree structure.  If a graph is not connected, its components are themselves trees; such a graph is called a forest. A forest may be disconnected, unlike a tree which must be connected.

\begin{definition*}
A \textbf{forest} is a graph whose components are trees.
\end{definition*}

\section*{Characterizing Trees and Spanning Trees}

The number of edges in a tree can be determined by the number of vertices it contains.  If we start with a connected graph $G$ and repeatedly remove edges until we obtain a tree $G'$, then the number of removed edges is related to the difference in the number of vertices between the original graph and the resulting tree. This process provides insights into the structure of spanning trees, which are subgraphs that connect all vertices without forming cycles.

