\section*{Bipartite Graphs and Their Characterizations}

A dominating set is a subset of vertices such that every vertex in the graph is either in the set or adjacent to a vertex in the set.  If a graph has no cycles, then any subset of its vertices forms a dominating set. Furthermore, if we have two dominating sets $A$ and $B$, their union contains all vertices of the graph, and the size of the smaller set is at most half the total number of vertices.

\textbf{Definition:} A \textit{bipartite graph} is a graph whose vertex set can be partitioned into two disjoint subsets $A$ and $B$ such that every edge connects a vertex in $A$ to a vertex in $B$.  In other words, there are no edges between vertices within the same subset. Trees, by their very nature (lacking cycles), are bipartite graphs. This property can be readily demonstrated by partitioning the vertices based on their distance from a chosen root node.

\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
    \node (v1) [circle, draw=black] {v1};
    \node (v2) [circle, draw=black] at (1,0) {v2};
    \node (v3) [circle, draw=black] at (2,0) {v3};
    \node (v4) [circle, draw=black] at (3,0) {v4};

    \draw (v1) -- (v2);
    \draw (v1) -- (v3);
    \draw (v2) -- (v4);
    \draw (v3) -- (v4);
\end{tikzpicture}

A crucial theorem states that a graph is bipartite if and only if it contains no odd cycles. An \textit{odd cycle} is a cycle containing an odd number of vertices, such as a triangle ($C_3$) or a pentagon ($C_5$).  The implication that the absence of odd cycles guarantees bipartiteness can be intuitively understood: any path within a bipartite graph must alternate between the two subsets $A$ and $B$, ensuring even length.

\begin{exambox}
A graph is bipartite if and only if it contains no odd cycles. \\ \textbf{Exam Tip:} Know this theorem and its significance in characterizing bipartite graphs.
\end{exambox}

This characterization provides a powerful tool for determining whether a given graph is bipartite.  Furthermore, the property of being bipartite serves as an invariant under isomorphism; if two graphs have different bipartiteness (one is bipartite, the other isn't), they cannot be isomorphic. This means that knowing whether a graph is bipartite can be used to distinguish between non-isomorphic graphs.
